Heanot, Derby: Interviewee's home}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid7670325\charrsid16072257 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid7670325 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Will you give me your name and your present address please?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Arthur Sharpe. 57 Lockton Avenue, Heanor, Derbyshire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You are married are you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Your year of marriage please?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 1928.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What year were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 1894.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Where were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Princes Street, Eastwood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How many years did you live in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I should say four years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And then where did you live?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I went to the Bridge. The Bridge is - at bottom of Eastwood - called the Bottoms in Sons and Lovers by D.H. Lawrence. That's t
he Bridge. Where he lived. He lived there for six years but before - before our family moved to there. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you move again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes, we moved again from the Breach into Walker Street. Again near to where D.H. Lawrence lived - about three or
 four doors away. And still in Eastwood but - no, rather in - in Greesley Parish but only just on the borders of Eastwood and Greesley. That sort of area. It's Eastwood now, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you stay in that house until the end of 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 We stayed in that house 'til 1915, my father built a house in Percy Street which is a cul-de-sac. Off the Eccl-s Street.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So you moved there in 1915?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 1915.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You stayed there for some years did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, yes, 'til father died. In 1951.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you remember why the family made these moves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well - we lived in a - a colliery company house in Princes Street, only a few doors from D.H. Lawrence was born in Victoria Street. Why - why they - actually went to the Breach, I'm not quite clear because it wa
s still in a company house, you see. Owned by the colliery. They were all owned by the colliery, all the - Scarborough Street, Wellington Street, Princes Street and the Breach but - it wouldn't be quite such a congested area. And - after we moved to the b
r
each - of course father was the only breadwinner you see, and my mother opened a shop in the Breach, selling sweets and all kinds of grocery ware and so on, you see. And that - that was - acted as a small income to - sort of help the family income. And of
 course naturally - family was getting larger as well, so there were more mouths to feed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You moved from the Breach, was this because your family was increasing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No, it wasn't because of that. But - they were connected with the Baptist church in Percy Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Your parents were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Parents were and we were sent there to Sunday school you see. But - to move to Walker Street from the Breach was a kind of a - little lift in the social scale. You see. To move out of a company house into a house owned by a private landlord.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 This was regarded as a move up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Regarded as a move up, the same as the Lawrences you see, they moved up - in the same sense from the Breach into Walker Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 They made sort of parallel moves to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The
y moved just before us, we followed each other round all the time sort of business, but it was only coincidental I think, nothing planned of course.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was this quite common, for people to improve themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well I shouldn't say it was common bec
ause - the majority of people that lived in the Breach they stayed put. They stayed put more or less but of course there were moves out but there's still families living there that were living there when I was a boy, or their }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 descendants}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  of course. But - t
hat was very interesting, that shop because - as I say it opened the avenues for the family and got in touch with people in the area and so on. And of course the - when they gave up the shop you see they just went into a - ordinary house and - father was 
the only breadwinner still and then he was a carpenter. You'll perhaps ask me that later though. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Four - four sisters and three brothers, there were eight in the family. But - the eldest brother die
d quite young. Before we went to the Breach actually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you give me the order of birth and how they were spaced out, starting with the oldest child down to the youngest child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well I was the fourth in the family. And - I was born in 1894. And 
I was the fourth in the family and - ordinary about the space of two years between each, perhaps a little bit over, a little bit under, you see, between each. There were two brothers older than me and one sister. And then three sisters and one brother you
nger. Eight - eight altogether, four of each. Yes, but one - one boy died so there were surviving four - four sisters and two brothers you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So you reckon it was approximately two years between each?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Approximately two years as far as I can remember, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How old was your father when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well he was born in '61. So he'd be thirty-three wouldn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well he was born in Lowerbill Vale. You see. Fairly near to the Breach. It's a continuation 
of the Breach up to above Eve colliery. And - my grandfather and mother lived in a cottage that was built on common land and owned by Lord Desborough who after - afterwards became Earl Cooper, you see, and they used to pay their - their rent quarterly. Th
e
 house is still standing on the corner of Moor Green, opposite the Horse and Groom, where the estate agent lived and they used to have to go there to pay their rent. You see, well that was - that was built on common ground, and all those cottages were. It
 
was a cottage in the centre of six hundred yards of ground. And all these cottages of course had their own pig sty and - all that kind of thing. You see, of course grandfather was a miner. My grandfather was a miner, worked at Bridely Colliery, same as D.
H. Lawrence's father.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Your father was quite a local man then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, he was - he was one of two brothers but his brother died rather young so there was only him in the family actually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What was your father's occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 A carpenter. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you know whether he had any other job apart from being a carpenter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
I don't think so. They - they did think about sending him down the mine but they didn't want - he didn't want that and I don't think his parents did eventually so - the
y put him to an apprenticeship under a Mr Durant of Eastwood. As an apprentice carpenter, he was in the building trade you see. He had this house and workshop just opposite the Congregational church in Albert street. It's there. Before - before those shop
s were built because - all that piece of land for the three - the bank and the three shops was reserved, we always called it the hospital ground. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 
That was left to build a hospital on and it was - it was empty for many, many years. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How they got round buildin
g shops and a bank on it one never knows. But they did get round that. Yes, he was a carpenter and - after he served his apprenticeship he worked for a Bob Walker Company at Langenhoe building railway wagons and repairing railway wagons and making such th
ings - as snow plough to fit in front of the locomotive and all that kind of thing you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So as far as you know he was a carpenter all his life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He was a carpenter all his life. Incidentally, that cottage - where he was a boy and where my gran
dparents lived and where I used to go many times of course - the old estate was sold just prior to the first world war. And all he gave for the cottage and six hundred yards of land was eighty pounds. Of course they'd paid for that over and over again by 
rent, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So he bought it then did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
He bought it, yes, well it came up for sale and - my grandparents weren't in a financial state to buy it because grandfather had been - well, he'd been on the sick list, you see he was a miner and in th
ose days there were no compensation for - bronchial disease as there is today you see. And - of course father came along and - it was to their interest to - to buy it. Which eventually - eventually was bought by my eldest brother, after the grandparents d
ied.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you ever remember your father having any casual or part time jobs in addition to the one he had as a carpenter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Not - only as a - a chapel caretaker that's all. He was interested in - other things that didn't bring any financial gain of
 course, or very little financial gain. He was on the educational committee of the Langden Co-op Society for - thirty-five years. He was the - he was the first man to retire into the - new rule when it was - resolved that all committee men should reside -
 retire at the age of seventy years, and he was the first one on any committee to retire under that new rule. He was also - very interested in the friendly societies and he was a - the - Manchester Unity Rising }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 Sun}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  Lodge at Eastwood, the Oddfellows. He went through all the offices of that. And }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 also}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  - went through all the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15805719  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
offices of the Eastwood Counties Conference and was made a life member of his services. So much so that the - in spite of the fact that there was only one bread earner - and the wages were r
ather low in those days - they put each member of the family into the - into the juvenile Lodge. You see. And I'm still reaping that benefit today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you ever remember your father being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No, he wasn't out of work, - not as being out of a job. But he had a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 
very}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 serious accident, when we were all children at home. That was - that was just after we left to walker Street. And - he had a - a piece of steel go right into the - the centre pupil of his eye. And he had to have several operations at - at Nottingham. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 Which meant him being out of work for a long, long time you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
And - had he not have been in any friendly society where he could come under the full benefit, there'd have been no income at all. No - National Insurance in those da
ys you see. But - we had friends who were very good. And - some friends organized a benefit concert for him, which brought him in quite a - quite a nice little bit and it helped the funds as well you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How old was your mother when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well she was - she was - she was two years younger than me father so she was would be born in 1863 wouldn't she. So she was about twenty-nine at that rate would she. Thirty-one, that's all, yes, that's all, thirty-one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well she came from Hilltop. Yes, her home was on Three Tuns Road. The cottage is still there which was her home, next to the top on the left. Before you get up to Edward Road, that was before Edward Road was built of course. Still in the Eastwood area, 
yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did she have any jobs before she was married do you know?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Yes, she was - yes, most of the girls you see in those days - I say most, well - a good number went into domestic service. And - she started as a housemaid, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 parlour maid}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  and then eventually as cook. And she was cook to John Player and Company - Nottingham. And you see - the cigarette people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did she live with them do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well she would do, yes, as cook. Oh definitely. And - we often used to say that - Mr Player would
 go down into the basement of the house - and come back with a container full - full of some kind of liquid, which they never found out what it was, but it was something to do with the manufacture of cigarettes. Yes, 'cos the - you see that's going back m
any years so Players would only be in the early days then. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 She was in domestic service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 She was in domestic service, before she was married, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did she do any work after she was married or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 None at all. Apart from this shop. That she opened. That's after - some of the children were born you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And no part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No part time jobs. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 If your mother, she had this shop, did anyone have to look after the children while your mother was looking after the shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh we were looking after one another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How many rooms were in the house you lived in Walker Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Three up and three down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How many reception rooms would you regard as being in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Two, two receptions rooms 'cos the other was a back kitchen you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did anybody else besides your brothers and sisters and parents live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No other relatives or lodgers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was the washing done at home or was it sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Always at home. We helped - when we get older of course. We helped as we got older, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your mother or father mend or make any of the families clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well mother used to do a lot of s
ewing and she made most of the clothes where she possibly could, and she made father's shirts and ours. On her - hand sewing machine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So she would make them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And repair them of course. Oh yes. Yes. Oh and knit - and knit stockings and socks as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What about shoes, did your father repair them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well apart from major repairs they were done at home. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your father help around the house in the normal sort of jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well you see, being a carpenter he could always lay his hand to all kinds of jobs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So he'd do some of the repairs and improvements in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did he do decorating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No, he didn't - he didn't do much decorating, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did he ever do things like washing up or cleaning of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh well, he'd help - he'd help of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And do the fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
He'd help of course, yes, and - of course - in those days you see, miners and the men who worked round the mine had allowance of coal. Perhaps a - perhaps a ton of co
al once a month in winter and six weeks in summer. And that meant that there was always a fire in the - in the grate. Used to put what they called the acre on. At night. That was a lump of coal before they went to bed, backed up by - by slack. So that me 
father came down at half past five in the morning - he'd have - all he'd got to do was just poke the fire and - and he'd put the kettle on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 This was like an all night fire before they brought out all night fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, that's right, yes, yes. Yes
, of course with being no hot water system there was always hot water in the boiler adjoining as well, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did he ever dress or undress the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did he ever bath them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - well he would - he would do occasionally, yes, 'cos that was - you usually bathed on Friday nights.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did he ever read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh yes, yes, he used to read and tell stories but - after that very serious accident he lost practically the whole sight of that eye. So he only had one eye you see and that was doing the work of two so - he would cut down that reading a good deal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did he take you out without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes. Once a week he was at Upnall. Near Token they call it. And sometimes he would get either one or two or 
three boys - on a Sunday, perhaps just occasionally because he was always engaged at the church or the Sunday school, or the church you see, but occasionally he would go and see his relatives in Upnall and we would walk from Walker Street right up the rai
lway line - from the top of Engine Lane right up to Watnell Colliery. Right up the railway line and then - come out there and go on to Upnall through the - what we used to call the allotments, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Would that be anywhere near where that brick quarry is now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
I suppose - yes, yes, up that - yes, in that area, yes, there are some cottages up there. Yes, yes, it is, yes, that's right. Of course Upnall's very nearby there - from there, yes. Yes, yes. Yes, that's right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 If your mother was would he look after you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh yes. Yes, you see - father was engaged in - as I said, the Educational worked and the Grove society and meetings at the - the friendly society, once a fortnight and - mother was interested in the - Co-operative Guild. And so t
hey would have to take one another off, as one was out one meeting he other would be at home and so on. Until the children got old enough to look after themselves, then they could be left of course. As far as - taking the children out you know, it was as 
high - it was a highlight of the year if we had half a day at the seaside. Half a day treat. Once a year. Oh yes,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Which would be on a Bank Holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well possibly on a Bank Holiday, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you have any little jobs in the house that you had to do regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, we had to wash up, we had to do the punching too on washdays. The punching.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That's with the washing thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes, that's right and - also turning the old mangle you know, the old mangle, there were no wring
ers then. The old fashioned mangle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 With the big wooden rollers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That's it, yes. That's the one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
How long did you continue to do these little jobs at home, did you do them after you left school, did you still carry on helping in the house after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh we should do little jobs of course after we left school but as time permitted because the - they were long hours in those days. My first job you see was half past six in the morning 'til five at night, five days - five nights
 - five and a half days a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Your brothers and sisters would be involved in these little domestic tasks as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You all sort of mucked in together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes, with the - my eldest brother went down the mine. You see, a
t the age of thirteen and my two eldest sisters went into domestic service so that kind of - relieved the pressure of the family a little bit you see. And - we then - with them being away in - in domestic - in domestic service it left more little jobs for
 the younger ones to do at home. Common practice - oh common practice that - generally common practice.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The older children would help the very young ones with things they found difficult
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, dress them, dress them and help to wash them and all that kind of thing. Take them to bed and so on, yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did the younger children help the older ones in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well not in the same - not in the same - not in the same ways, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I suppose a younger child could help an older one in exceptional circumstances?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh yes, yes, if it was necessary. Yes, there was one - there was on incident - while we were at home, young, that I call to mind. It just shows you the - the way that we had to do even - operations, surgical operations in 
those days. My third sister had trouble with her tonsils, and the doctor came and took them out on the couch in the kitchen. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And you can remember that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh definitely, she bit him as well and he always remembered that. Yes, yes, she left a m
ark in his finger, definitely. That was rather a crude way but it happened. Just shows you. And also I remember}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15805719  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
my father taking me to the local doctor to have a molar taken out. No anesthetic in those days. What an experience it was. Yes, not }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4348900\charrsid15805719 an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 an}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4348900\charrsid15805719 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 esthetic.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 When you were a schoolboy were you expected to go to bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well reasonable time. I suppose - half past six, seven time. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4348900\charrsid15805719 Of}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  course as you got a little bit older you got an extension.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Who put you to bed, did your mother take you to bed when you were very small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes. Or father would if mother was engaged otherwise of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you remember at about what age you would go to bed yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - I should think when we - well after we - before we got
 to work - before we started to work, we'd take one another to bed. We were three brothers in one bed. You see. And sometimes if the bed was a bit crowded there'd be two at the top and one at the bottom. Feet to feet you know. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So at times there would be three boys in the one bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The eldest girls went away into domestic service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Your mother and father would have a room to themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And the girls would sleep in the other room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 There were three bedrooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, that's all, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Would you bath in the living room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, in the living room - in the front of the fire you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 About }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 how}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 often would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - once a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was it the practice then to have clean clothes when you had a bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What room did the family have their meals in generally speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 In the - in the kitchen, not - not the back kitchen, the living room. What we called the living room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were there any special occasions when you would eat in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Be very rare. Very rare.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well she cooked in the same room because there was a cooking range in there you see. And it was on a range, yes, the old -
 the old range you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 When was breakfast eaten, when you were a boy what time would you sit down for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh around about eight o'clock because we had to be at school by nine and if we had to run a little errand or do a little job you s
ee in between. And the school was half a mile away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Who would be there at the breakfast table at the same time as you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - the children that were at home of course. Yes. And mother, yes. 'Cos father went to work very early.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Your father had already gone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you remember what you usually had to eat or drink for breakfast during the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well I suppose the usual tea and - what we used to call soaky.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What's that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That's - that's bread soaked in the tea. You 
see, and - we used to call it soaky. And of course occasional bacon and - but not every morning of course, there wasn't - there wasn't the means in those days. And if we had an egg we had half of one. One between two. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So Sunday breakfast might be a little bit different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes, we all sit down together as far as possible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The actual food would be different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, we used to always have bacon on Sunday mornings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What would the midday meal consist of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - we
 should - we should have - the ordinary dinner of course. Meat and potatoes and pudding but - unless we waited until father came home at half past five and had it with him but normally we had it in the midday, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You came home from school did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
We came home from school, of course school was only half a mile away. We always came home from school. But on Sunday of course - we always had the Sunday joint, always had a special dinner - the hot joint and vegetables and - and pudding and - ver
y often on a Sunday, you see at the church in those days there were no resident ministers so we had lay - lay Pastors - lay preachers rather, who used to come from Nottingham and surrounding areas so that meant entertaining the preacher for the day, to di
n
ner and tea. And - the various people connected with the church would take it in turns to entertain these people. But we had them very often, made some very good friends too. And - one gentleman who came to - to our house quite a lot and became very frien
d
ly, him and his family too afterwards, was very intrigued on his first visit for hanging out of the boiler at the side of the fire was a long string and he wondered to himself, now what's at the end of that string? Until after the first course - mother wo
u
ld open the lid and pull the string and out came a large jam roll that had been cooking all the morning, you see. That was cooked in a large - having a special saucepan on the fire. And he - he used to speak about that very often. Yes. We generally, well 
we very often had that on Sunday. Of course we had other - other things as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What about the evening meal, when would that be, when you came home from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 When we came home from school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That would be like a tea would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, just an ordinary tea, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was that a bit special on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh yes. Oh yes, if - had a tin of fruit or - or prunes or figs or something like that you know. Occasionally tin of salmon if you could manage it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your mother bake her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, always. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 
You see with having the - the - miners' coal - there was always a fire and - it was customary in those days, all the miners used - miners' wives used to bake their own bread. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
And they used to go to the stores with their pillowslips for the flour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So your mother made her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What about jam, did she ever make jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did she bottle fruit or anything like that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, she'd bottle fruit. 'Cos we had a - we had a common garden attached to me grandfather's of about two }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  two}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719  allotments}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  together - the ground in which the cottage stood and adjoining one so there was always fruit and apples and so on you know. Plenty of rhubarb of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What about pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, she'd do all pickles. Pickled onions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Home made wine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Occasionally. But - herb beer. Oh used to - used to make herb beer in those days you know, herb beer. Dandelions and - and that - that kind of thing you know, make herb beer. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You'd grow vegetables and fruit in your common garden with your grandfather?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You had to buy some at times did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh - oh yes, that'd be in the wintertime, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were there any tinned fruit about in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 We had tinned fruit but - not in the proportion that you have today of course. They used to run more on the dried fruit. It was cheaper.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were there such a thing as dried vegetables in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Very little - in those days. Mostly fresh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your family keep any livestock, any hens or pigs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh yes. We used to - used to keep a - bantams as we called them. That's the small poultry. Both at the Breach and at Walker Street and of course we always had rabbits.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 But were they pets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 They were pets. Oh yes, they were pets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Who looked after the hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - of course the boys would - would have to feed those.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you remember how many times a week you would eat meat in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well you see from the Sunday joint 
- there was always cold meat on Monday. And then it would be hashed up, you see, to make it last as far as it possibly could. And then of course - later on in the week there'd be always pigs fry or a fish meal you see. Used to have a lot of sprats from ma
rket on Friday nights. Don't see much of them today but it's a very small fish. And they were very cheap and very tasty too. Oh of course very often mussels on Saturday afternoon - for tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Would you buy them from Eastwood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. There was a market in Eastwood in those days. At front of the Sun Inn. Oh yes, no traffic then in those days, only horses and }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 carts}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
. Oh always market there with - with open fires for the fish and chip stalls you know and the meat stalls and lots of stalls. Well that was the first place - first meeting held there of the Midland Railway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 In 1830 something wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
I should - it would be about that because you see when the collieries were being opened up - the coal was transported by the canal on - by barges on
 the canal until - the collieries were getting more plentiful, there was more coal being - hewn. They wanted a quicker way of transport, so they - decided to - have this railway you see, and - and that's the - beginning of the Arrowash Valley Line. To tra
nsport the coal along the Arrowash Valley.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I think there's a plaque outside?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, there was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 1832 when it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes, I couldn't remember the date. That's it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That's got a bit of history attached to it hasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, it has.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you ever have any tinned meat can you remember as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Very little. There weren't so much tinned meat in those days. There was bully beef you know but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was that before or after the war or during the war, can you remember?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well the - there'd be a certain amount I suppose before the war, but very little. It came into prominence during the first world war didn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you ever have any extra meat, things like a rabbit from poaching or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Use
d to have rabbit but not by poaching. We - we had an uncle who had the farm at the Heights, next to where D.H. Lawrence was. There were two - there were two farm houses next to one another. My uncle, Mr and Mrs W. Pearson had that. And the Chambers had th
e other one. Well we'd get the rabbit from there occasionally. The Chambers. That's right, D.H. Lawrence's - where he used to visit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Professor Chambers was the one who died last year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That's right, died last year, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He was a professor in history wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
That's right, yes, well there's something in the Journal yesterday about - they're going to form a fund to - in memory of him. Yes. Historical Society and the Nottingham area. Yes, yes, oh yes. Of course -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And that's where Lawrence used to go and visit then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh yes. Yes, you see, he - he lived on Walker Street, only about six doors from where we lived, and - but - him being nine years my senior, his journeys to the Heights would be before my time. So about the end of his journeys were the beginning of mine.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Where was the Hags in relation to Walker Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well the Hags was - on the way to Almsley, the other side of Underwood. Near Pwlleli, down Fairley Hill. That features in his - Sons and Lovers and other - oth
er books as well. Yes. Yes. Just off the slip side of Underwood there. The Hags. Overlooking the reservoir.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Do you remember seeing your mother having less food so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was it the practice for your father to have more if there wasn't much to go round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well you see, he - with him being the breadwinner of course, he - he had to be looked after but - he wouldn't have it at the expense of the children of course.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were you allowed to talk during meals or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well - not too much. Within reason of course but - there was a kind of children should be seen and not heard in those days. To some extent anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I think it was a little bit flexible?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Oh yes, it was flexible but it wasn't strict in our household to that extent, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to have a bit of everything that was put in front of you?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well normally - we had to have what was there. And if we - made up our mind we didn't want it, well it was there for the next meal.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What would your mother say if you left some food uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well of course, if you weren't - if you weren't well or something like that there'd be - there'd be a 
reason for it but normally you'd be expected to eat it of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
If there was something on the table that you wanted could you ask for it to be passed to you or did you have to wait until somebody offered it to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh no, you could - you could ask for it if you wanted it, it wasn't - it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 wasn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  that strict.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh yes, if - if there was a second helping to be had. Specially at pudding time you see. That was one feature that - when we went as children to
 the Hags, to my uncle and aunt's - they had a family of five daughters and a son, but unfortunately the son died very young so the - the girls had to do a lot of the work on the farm. And when we sat down to dinner - we always had the pudding first, you 
s
ee, being on a farm there was plenty of milk. And pearl barley in those days, so we had a lovely pearl barley pudding you see. Therefore you didn't want a lot of meat and vegetables after. Well that wasn't our custom at home. No. Not ours. Oh yes, well we
 always had it at - at my uncle's farm. Always. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were you taught to hold your knife and fork and sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well we - we had to sit reasonably at the table of course and - and use the knife and fork properly as far as we could, oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Could you bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Not toys, not at meal times if that's what you mean. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well we used to - always to be asked to leave if we wanted to leave before the rest of the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 All the family sat at the table for the meal except when your father was at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, and - in - in the main, yes, when we were at home, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you have the same place at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well normally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You knew where you'd got to sit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You knew where you'd got to sit normally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How was the meal served, who would }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 serve}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Mother would serve meals of course. Father would always carve - carve the Sunday joint.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was there any special order that you were served in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
No, I don't think so. Not - no necessarily. Perhaps just depends what - those people who had started work you see they'd perhaps have the first - the first turn round.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Where did the very young ones sit before they could sit up at the table and feed themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well, there was always - there was always a chair where they could - they could sit with a kind of a little table as well you see at the front.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Like the forerunner of the modern high chair?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, you could have the potty underneath you know and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Who would feed them, one of the older girls or your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, one of the elder girls. Yes, they could do, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was your mother an easy person for you to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, we could talk
 to her, within reason, but she always - demanded you know that we should be - proper - have proper manners and - she would - she would be strict without being too strict.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did she show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh - all the time. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 If you had any worries could you share them with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh - oh yes, we could, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was your father easy to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh yes, he was easy to talk to, he was - he's a very even tempered man, my father was, but - if there was any time when we'd been misbehav
ing and - mother had to tell him when he came home from work he could just - lay the heavy hand on a little bit but not too much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Would he show affection to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Oh yes, definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Could you share worries with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well we - we were brought up - you see to respect and revere the parents and naturally it fell into line that - they were affectionate to us and it was - it was being responded to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did they bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in certain ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh to be - to be brotherly and - and sisterly in that sense, oh yes, we - on the whole the atmosphere of the home was - pretty good. But - of course there's always little incidents that crop up in home life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 If someone hit you were you told to hit back or what was their attitude?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - there had to be some reason for that - it wouldn't be - in a - in a - in aggressive streak you see. Or - if there wa
s a time when - that - that we'd been beaten by any other boy and there was no reason for it, of course they'd complain at home and there'd be some kind of response in that sense to the other parents if necessary or to the other boy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What kind of person do you think your parents hoped you would grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well you see, in those days - there was not - not much opportunity for - after school education, you see, and there was no grants and - well, we couldn't apply for any grant I mean, there w
as one - there was one breadwinner and that was it. And as soon as you were able to leave school well you had to begin to think about earning something. That was a natural - our come. And - it wasn't that - would you like to be so and so, it wasn't the fi
r
st job that came along if there was a suitable situation came along well that was it. Of course my elder brother - decided he wanted to go down the mine, I didn't - I never fancied going down the mine. So of course I - I went into other - sphere of labour
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 But you can't remember your parents ever saying they would like you to grow to be a certain thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No. I can't say that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did they bring you up to consider certain things in life as important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well, telling the truth and - bei
ng honest and - and - friendly with the neighbours and that kind of thing and of course - being - church people and - father being superintendent and being at the church, and mother being interested as well, of course - we were brought }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 up}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  in that atmosphere. And - if there was a time when we transgressed, well if - if the punishment was necessary well it was administered.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What about swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your parents ever say anything about swearing, that you shouldn't do it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well we weren
't allowed - we weren't allowed to do that, or mix among company where - where it was used if possible. And there was none of that in the home of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 If you were in company with grown ups and they were taking were you allowed to join in as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well not to but in. If there was a - if there was a - discussion that we were concerned with we might be asked - what we thought.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 If you did something that your parents thought was wrong what would happen, would they punish you in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well - when we were at the Breach - of course we had to run errands on Saturday mornings, as mother being busy in the shop, and we were given some money, two of us, my elder brother and me were given some money to go to Eastwood to do some shopping and
 on the way we stopped playing marbles with other boys. Well - strange to say when we wanted to collect them, we'd given the money to another boy to hold. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 
And when we came to collect it, it wasn't there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So we weren't able to do the shopping. And of course
 the punishment of that was we were sent to be straight away. Sent to bed straight away without any dinner. You see. That was sufficient punishment in itself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was it your mother who sent you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 She would give you this punishment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You wouldn't be punished severely very often then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh no. It had - it had to be - it had to be called for, yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 If necessary your father would administer some sort of punishment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes. Because his hand was heavy enough for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 When you were punished for this marbles business, can you remember how you felt about being punished for it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well of course when you receive punishment you always feel a little bit resentful but I suppose in a case - in t
hat case we'd asked for it so that was it. The same as you see - as boys at school - that's what I say is wrong with the present system - is boys at school if we misbehaved we got punished and that was it. But - looking aback on it -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Do you remember how you felt on this particular occasion when you were punished for playing marbles instead of going on your business?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well of course I said as - we were - we were resentful of course but - because we'd done wrong and - weren't trustworthy in letting 
the other boy hold the money so of course that was it. But - there was another occasion when - I don't just know what it was now but my elder brother had done something and he was sent to bed and while we were playing in the yard below he wanted to have a
 
look of course and - in the process he pushed his head through the window, you see, so that - that - instead of having punishment to such an extent on that, although father was told about it when he came home on the Saturday dinnertime - I don't know whet
h
er they were sorry or whether he was - whether he was something a little bit different anyway they made up their minds to take us to Nottingham and buy some new clothes on the Saturday afternoon. You see. I just forget now what it was. Anyway he pushed hi
s head through a window and - yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Would you say that you received your ideas about how you had to behave from both of your parents or one more than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No, I should thing together generally. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day, did you have a special sort of meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well we'd have perhaps a little party with the children you know and perhaps one or two playmates but - nothing - nothing great. There wasn't - there wasn't the money in those days to make a spread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was it normal to receive a present or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 It'd be very small. Very small. Perhaps a very small one you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you remember anything you did with your mother or father together on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh -
 well - well that's one thing that I - going to talk about. When we lived in the Breach - on Christmas morning - there was a treat for every boy or girl who liked to walk up to Anclose House, the home of Major Barber. Only of course he - he wasn't Major B
arber then 'cos it was his father that was in residence then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He was the owner of the local coal mine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
He was - that's right. Of course it was Barber and Walkers. It's the Barber - they used to tell me when I was a boy that - Walker - Squire Walk
er lived at Eastwood Hall and - the finance and Barber's the brains. You see, and - I know I've heard my grandfather say that - Squire Walker - used to get some of the colliery boys and - to play cricket across - they had an Eastwood }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 Colliery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  cricket groun
d, they had about three - three teams - three very good teams there. The Breach was a proper training ground for Nottingham cricketers. Oh yes. It definitely was. And we had some very good teams there. Well, the young Squire used to get some of the collie
r
y boys and put a sovereign on the middle peg, you see, and if the bowler knocked it off that was his. Because you see he had plenty of brass. But - with regard to walking up to - Anclose House there was always a new penny for every child who - who went on
 
that Christmas morning. You see. Always a new penny. And - that might seem - might not seem much in present day standards but - as I've put down in those memories there, it would buy four ounce of boiled sweets or four farthing candles on bonfire night. I
n those days, so to us it was a lot of money }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 see. It definitely was. Yes, well talking about Christmas, of course we always hung our stocking up you know before - before going to bed. But - there was no expensive toys in those days. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 
You see if we had an apple and a few nuts and a sugar pig and - perhaps a small toy and an apple, rosy apple that was about the extent, but when there's six of you, you see, six stockings to fill - it makes a lot of difference. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 With regard to - when we had the shop in - in th
e Breach - we had a ha'penny a week pocket money. And we had to spend it at our own shop. So we used to walk round the block and come back and walk into the shop door and spend it. You see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were there any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. O
h yes, we had - my father bought a - a brand new Bell Organ from - it was a United States make, the Bell Organ from - the man who had a music shop in Eastwood, I just forget his name now. And - my oldest sister had the first lessons on it. But when we mov
ed to Walker Street I had - a lot of lessons under a man named Mr William Templeman. He used to give }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 me}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  an hour}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
s lesson every week for the payment of a shilling. A shilling an hour. But I didn't go too very far with it but - I was always interested and I got to - to get to be the church organist in later years and choirmaster.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So it helped you anyway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
It helped me, yes, it gave me a - it gave me a basic - training for the music, yes. But - father could always - play a little bit on the - on the what we used to call the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 melodeon}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 , it was - a forerunner of the piano }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 accordion}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 of the present day. And he worked on the musical box as well in those days. Yes. Mechanical musical box.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was there anyone in the family who sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Not - well -
 I say yes - we were always interested, the three of us brothers were in the Eastwood and Greesley male voice choir. That was a choir formed before this present day - colliery male voice choir. And Mr - Mr Templeton was the choir master for quite a bit, y
o
u see, and - I - the school concerts at the chapel, they used to have different turns and I was the - I was the - man who sang the comic and humorous songs and - I never got to further than - being paid seven and six for two songs on one occasion. After s
ome Co-op - Co-op festival, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did the family ever make a musical evening together?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Not together, no. No, my sister was a very nice contralto singer, but in the choir but not a soloist.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your parents play any games with you when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well - in the home - in the home you know. Oh yes, we used to have some - table games of some sort sometimes and - a favourite game that my father had - when we were youngsters, he used to lie on his back you know and - get our feet on hi
s hands and throw us over his - over his knees. You see, it was a very - very favourite great game with the young children in those days. He used to often do that. Of course he - he used to often get on - oh his - oh his knees and sing to us. Oh yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What about playing cards and dominoes or draughts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, we'd have dominoes but never cards. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were there any books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Not to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 many. Not too many books. Just a few, been handed down, that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What about newspapers and magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
We always had the - what we used to call the Eastwood Rag. That's the Eastwood and Kimberley Advertiser once a week on a Friday night, that's the only paper we had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Do you remember your father or mother reading, did they both read regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well mother used to read a lot. Oh especially when we got a bit older when she'd more spare time. She used to read a lot but as I said father didn't do much reading on account of this injury to his eye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did they ever read aloud to you or to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Not very much. Occasionally but not very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Do you remember a funeral in the family when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 
My Godfather - who'd been ill many years - he died in 1914 and when he was - while he was - sick, that was the time they opened the - Notts and Derby tramways from Ripley to Nottingham. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
That was the - it was supposed to be the longest privately owned - tramway in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 Britain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
. Fourteen miles, whether that's so or not I can't say but I always - I remember - laying the
 electric cable right away and laying all the tramway lines and all of that - all the lot. And incidentally - perhaps a lot of people don't know this or perhaps don't remember but from Hilltop along Dovecote Road and down what we used to call Bramley Line
 
to Bellevue pit they had a special cable laid for the colliery. Well - after the cable was laid they must have altered their minds and they built a power station. So they generated their own electricity. And I should imagine that cable's still there. And 
as a special treat my father had a - a horse and landau to take me grandfather round to see the tramway when it was first opened - in 1913. And he - he died in - in 1914. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you remember who attended the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - well - most of the family. I know we - we two eldest boys had new black shoes I remember for that occasion. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was it the practice for you all to wear mourning clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 It was in those days, yes. Of course the younger members of the family wouldn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were you taken out visiting neighbours and friends or relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well we had - we had relatives in the area of course. We had an aunt near - near Bury and they had children about our own age and of course with this aunt - Mrs Pearson - who was my mother's 
eldest sister lived up Hags farm, of course we used to go over there in the summertime and - did a little bit of haymaking, and fetching the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 cows}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  and clapping the birds off the corn and all that. You see, but we never went more than two at a time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Would you go on your own or did someone take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well - no, we went on our own because we didn't go 'til we were old enough you see perhaps two boys or perhaps one boy and a girl would go. One day in the summer holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were you ever taken out shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes, I used to often go to - with me mother on Friday night to the market. Yes, from Walker Street, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You said you went out sometimes with just your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. That was up to my relatives at Upnell. Yes. Yes. Of course
 there was always the grandfather and grandmother, we spent a lot of time there. Because it weren't too far away. At Lowerboar Vale. Off Engine Road. Rose Cottage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you ever go out with just your father on a Bank Holiday?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - same as I say, we had half day trips you see to the seaside but mother and father would go as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well I - I did. My father had some relatives who lived at - Sherwood Rise in Nottingham and they had two boys about my ow
n age and I went - to spend a week with them, occasionally - in Nottingham, in Sherwood Rise, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 But not regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Not regularly - not regularly - no. No, see there was no money for holidays in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How did you spend your Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Still a schoolboy? Well - of course the - we had to - we had to - look after the children, do some shopping, you see and - we were given certain duties to do and when - when you'd done that you can go out to play, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How About Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well Sunday, well it was Sunday school morning and afternoon, you see. And of course - and then the older children could stay at home and look after the young ones while the parents went to church at night, which was only a few yards away. And also - 
my parents being caretakers for quite a while of the Percy Street Baptist church, they had little duties there to do you see and doing sweeping up or dusting the - the pews ready for Sunday and that kind of thing. Help to get the coal in and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you have different clothes on on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes. We always had a new suit on anniversary day. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 
New clothes for - for Sunday school anniversary, and they always last us about a year you see,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15805719  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 
well next anniversary we should have a new one and take the - those for - wear to school in the daytime.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your parents think it wrong to play on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. We were never allowed to go out to play on Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And they thought it wrong to work on a Sunday as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Your parents did attend a place of worship didn't they?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What denomination was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Baptist. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 They would go quite frequently then, how often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well you see, there was always the - Sunday activities. My father was a S
unday school superintendent and he was also Deacon of the church for a good many years. And - and then there'd be different meetings in the week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So they were quite regular attenders?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You would attend mostly on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Mostly on a Sunday and then of course - prior to the Sunday school anniversary there was always about six weeks practice, about one or two nights a week. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were there any Sunday school outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Not outings as such but we had Sunday school 
treats. You see, there was always the - the bun feast as we used to call it and the brass band you know, used to parade the district with this - silk banner, you see, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 and come}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  back for a - a tea and then go into a field to play games and so on. But - there
 was - a Band of Hope in connection with the Eastwood Congregational church. We used to go there and we had an outing to Codnor Park Monument about once a year. Condor Park. But you see - we were able to go up the monument and view the countryside but of 
course that's all closed now, they won't climb - it's not safe. They haven't allowed anybody up for quite a number of years now. That's about the only outing we had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you think of any other activities organized by the church that you took part in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No - no, not very much, of course there was the - Christian }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 Endeavour}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  and - things like that, but in the week there wasn't really too much. Not for children until they got a little bit older of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you belong to a choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Oh yes, I was in the choir.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were there any choir activities?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Choir practice once a week. Generally. Perhaps a little bit more we was get - getting ready for Harvest Festival and - and Sunday school anniversary and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was there a temperance club attached to the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was there anything else, any other club organized by the church or chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 There was - you see - in those days there was not much - youth organizations sort of thing as there is today you see and the - yo
ung people used to make their own fun, we - we used to go - on Sunday night after - this is getting a little bit later on of course - after the service the young people used to get together and go round to each others house 'cos most people had an organ o
r a piano, we used to get round these instruments and sing. Take it in turn going round, perhaps a cup of tea before we came away or something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was grace said at meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 By whom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Father generally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were you taught to say your prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you ever have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Didn't have family prayers as such, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your father take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No, not to that extent. Apart from the Co-operative movement, but that wasn't in the political field as it is today. There were no }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 joining}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 up with the Labour - well the Labour party didn't exist then. It was only two parties in those days. And - there was always a big affair you know when there was an election. Much so - much more so than it is today. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you remember your father voting in a general election before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I suppose - he would vote at local elections and general elections but - how he voted of course that was left to him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You don't know which party he voted for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I should imagine he'd be Liberal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
We're told that in some places men felt that they were risking their jobs or their houses if they voted differently from their employers, do you know if your father felt himself under any pressure at any time to vote for a particular party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I shouldn't think so. I shouldn't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He wasn't a member of a political party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No, not as such, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He didn't work for any of the parties at an election?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Nor your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 They didn't take any part in any political activities other than the election?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No. When there was a - a strike on - going back in the early days - I should think it'd be 1921 strike probably - or one
 before that, 'cos there was several strikes in the coalfield, but there was a very big strike in 1921 and a general strike in 1926. Well - along with others - on the Education Committee and the Co-op Society they organized soup kitchens. And father was v
ery active in that you see and he was also active in the - in the Juvenile Lodge, preparing the outing we had - always had an outing there. You see, not an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 outing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  but a special day. Special day for the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7163663\charrsid15805719 Juvenile}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  Lodge.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Your father had quite a variety of interests then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Oh yes. Yes. Yes, the Rising Sun Oddfellows, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your mother have any interests outside the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 She - oh yes, she - she attended the Co-op Guild, she was quite a - in the Co-op Guild. When the children got off hand a little bit.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did she ever go out to enjoy herself, any social occasion can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
No, not - not - not too much I shouldn't think. They did go on - she went to represent the Co-op Guild too at one or two of the - yearly sessions, 
when the children got a little bit off hand of course. And father and mother went twice - as delegates from the Rising Sun Lodge, 'cos me father was a trustee and office bearer and they went to Guernsey and they went up to Hull I think it was. For a week 
you see. On deputations.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What time did your father get home from work in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
He was at - from half past five in the morning 'til five o'clock at night. Used to get home about half past. And sometimes - when we were at home from school, 
during the summer, mother would pack a hot lunch up and send a couple of us down to where he worked with a hot lunch for him. 'Cos - but in the ordinary he would have that when he came home at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How many evenings a week would he spend at home, or how many evenings a week would he go out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well he - he - he never went out only when he'd got to go to the - either church or the particular activities.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Which would be how often, a couple of nights a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - perhaps not quite so much
 as that. Of course, in summer time - grandfather wasn't able to do his garden so father used to take we boys down and we had to do both gardens, between us. Yes. Yes, that's so. And so that took a lot of time up in the summertime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Your father didn't attend pubs or clubs then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your father take part in any sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No, not as - he used to - used to enjoy working a game of cricket, he didn't take part in it himself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did he ever attend the races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He wasn't a betting man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Your father belonged to a society, was it a kind of savings club come sick club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What was it called?
