ime father wanted her in - in the daytime or in the night for the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12523590\charrsid15805719 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 on}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 finement you see. Oh yes. For when she was having her children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 A district nurse you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No. No. Well there were - there were women in those days that weren't registered 
maternity nurses, but used to do that kind of thing, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 It was recognized that they were doing it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 But not on an official basis?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No, that's so but - there were - there were friends and neighbours that could be called in if 
- if mother was ill like that but - she used to nurse herself a good deal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your parents have any relatives living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes - of course me father, as I told you before, he lost his only brother you see and of course - grandmother and grand
father - grandfather died in 1914, I think he'd be 1918 my grandmother died. And so we - we were always used to going backwards and forwards there you see. And then me mother had sisters, she had a sister at Hilltop. Lived - lived near the - church - the 
C
hurch Army. Mission church up there. Quite near then, remember there was this one at the Hags farm you see. But the others were further away, they'd been in - one was still in domestic service. She was a housekeeper for a German down in London. 'Til she d
ied really, she was maiden - maiden aunt.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Would you see these relatives quite regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes, fairly - fairly regularly. Oh yes, fairly regularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 They would see them at their homes, they would drop in and see them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well occasionally. Occasionally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your parents have regular friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well father always had friends in the Co-op movement and the - in the Lodge you know and - mother had friends at the Guild besides - women that we'd grown up with sort of thing you know. But they never }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 neighboured}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 . They - they never neighboured in that sense - running backward and forwards into each others' houses if you understand what I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Most of their friends were either from the to-op movement?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Or the church of course. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And the Lodge?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. That's so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did they generally share the same friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, I think mainly speaking they had no separate - people. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your mother have any friends of her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Not - not apart from her si
sters I don't think and - the women that she mixed with at the Guild of course. Yes. She were in the Guild. Yes, it's for women, Women}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 s Co-operative Guild you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And she would see them there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes, that's so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And your father would have one or two friends in the Oddfellows?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes. Oh yes, he had, he had quite a few friends there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were friends ever invited back to the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - sometimes - a Deacon and his wife would come in - after the Sunday evening service y
ou see, occasionally. And of course there was - there was also a lot of friends rallied round when me father had his accident. You see, people popping in to see how he was and - and that kind of thing. See what they could do.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 When people came - when the Deacon came - would they stay for anything to eat or drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No, just a - just a casual - just a casual visit, half an hour perhaps, just to chat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The particular occasion when you had callers was when your father had his accident wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well that was - that was perhaps the outstanding time to remember. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 But apart from that there weren't any special occasions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No - no special occasions, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did people call in on a special day, the Deacon, that would be a special day wouldn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Yes, 'cos the - 'cos you see there was a number of Deacons and - and at that time there was no minister so the Deacon took the church sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The sort of people who came to the home, would you say they were mother's or your father's friends or both?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well both - both generally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did any friends call in casually without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - well not - not in the main I shouldn't think, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Nor neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well you see there was - the house w
here we lived in Walker Street, there was two houses at one entry so there was always neighbours - door to door if you understand, 'til they built the barrier between.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your parents ever go out to visit friends or neighbours in their homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 W
ell, occasionally. Occasionally. Yes, they always had contacts, as I say, at these particular - movements and they'd visit one another occasionally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 People used to make their own amusements rather more in those days?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 They certainly did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What did your parents do when they were with their friends or neighbours on a sort of social evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
My father was always - always fond of a game of whist. But - as far as - playing for money or anything like that that was out of course. Oh yes. And mother - mother had no particular games I don't think in that sense.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What about music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well - the musical evenings that we had was when - when I used to bring the young folk - after Sunday evening service and we get round the organ in the front room. You see, and - that'd be my friends. They were my friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 This didn't apply to your parents and their friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So the main purpose of the social activities then was more or less a common interest and chat and conversation and the odd game of cards?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, that's it. Yes. Yes, that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Many people divide society into different social classes or groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 They do, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 In that time before 1918 did you think of some people belonging to one group and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well there was always the - type of the aristocracy with regard to the officials of the colliery. You see, they always had the white waistcoat and the gold yard and so on and - a kind of an air of superiority sort of thing and that's where the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 butties'}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 lump came in. You see. Oh yes. But - they weren't - they weren't unreachable in that sense but they was always looked upon as a little bit - the same when there was the - the chemist in Eastwood who had a son, Captain Chambers, he was - 
he was perhaps in that class but - he organised }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 B}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 oys}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 \rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 B}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
rigades and Cadet Corp and that sort of thing and - plenty of his boys went into the first world war, in the Red Cross, R.AM.C. See, with their training.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So you'd get some sort of business people and then the elite of the colliery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 More or less a sort of middle upper class group?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, that's so. Yes, that's so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Then you'd have the rest of the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Mainly miners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Of course - a little bit higher up perhaps there'd be the - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 
owners}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  - owners of the colliery and - and people in that category, perhaps a little bit - you know - they were the bosses and they paid themselves and the wages of course and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The colliery owners would be regard at the upper class would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Which class or group did you and your family belong to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well we were working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What sort of people belong to this class, it wasn't just miners was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh no, oh no, there was same 
as father, he was a carpenter you see and - men - engineers and that sort of thing and - men who worked down the mine what we called a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 huff}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 er}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 , that was men in charge of the horses. We used to call the h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 ffler. Yes, that's right. And of course then there w
as men in charge of the main road. The main road in the colliery, running from the pit bottom to the different kinds of workings. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 
You see, they had charge - of the main road, well then you see, my grandfather, besides being a butty he became a deputy. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That
 mean he had to go in and see the workers were safe before the men went into work, see if the props were put - see if the props were set - set properly and - and the roof was safe. Yes. And he used to have to go perhaps at three o'clock in the morning. Yo
u see, up to this Brigsey Colliery. Same colliery where Mr Lawrence worked. But me father was before Mr Lawrence's time - before you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That was David Lawrence's father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That's it. Arthur Lawrence. That was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The term butty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That was a miner who had a section or a seam of coal to dig out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
He had - yes, he had charge of a certain stall. What is called a stall. He was the man - and he had to pay his men, whether he got any return for himself or not. You see, in those 
days there wasn't a guaranteed wage - for a miner. The men - and he sometimes had a - a bad stall and a good stall. It was called a stall you see. And it depended on the amount of coal that was turned out - in proportion to the amount that they were going
 to receive at the weekend.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So the Butty had to take a bit of a gamble then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He'd got to work out how much he'd get out of it to pay his men?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That's so, and you see sometimes they - they'd have a thin seam or a larger s
eam or they'd run up against some faults. You see, that wouldn't - wouldn't give the coal return. And - in that sense - that introduced a bit of bribery. Because it has been known that - the other miners has received an orange and when he's opened it ther
e
's been a sovereign in it. That has been known. That kind of thing you see to get a good stall. Yes. Yes. You see, there's no guaranteed wage. I heard my grandfather say once, after he'd paid his men he got sixpence for himself. And you see the miners in 
t
hose days never saw daylight in winter. Early morning you see 'til - yes. Yes. Six and a half days a week. And - sometimes - - it wasn't - it wasn't generally - but sometimes - down in the Breach particular but not on Walker Street, as I say we were a lit
tle bit higher up the social scale - they would sit on their haunches to - well after they'd had their dinner at night you see, if - if the weather was warm and if they were resting before they got ready for bed. But that - that was only }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 general}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  - it wasn't general, but occasionally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 Butties'}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  lump then was for the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well it - they called - the butties}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 ump}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 was the idea of going to that certain chapel the officials went. You see. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Like a community within a community?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, that's so, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And they would go there and meet each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. I - I suppose so, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So they got the term butties}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  lump?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you remember when you were a child being brought up to treat people of one group different to people from another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
No, not - not generally speaking I don't think, no. Of course - we always - had a special respect perhaps for the headmaster and teachers at school. - you see?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And presumably the vicar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes. Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were you taught to touch your cap to people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You were expected to call the teacher sir were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Anybody else that you were expected to call sir that you can remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - of course we - my brother and m
yself were in the Boys Brigade and - of course there was always the - the Captain. Captain Chambers you see, he - he had that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What about Master or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No, I don't think so. No, not - Mr and Mrs it was generally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you remember anyone showing respect to your parents in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - of course my father was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 superintendent}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  in the school, the Sunday school. In the Sunday school. And - the - the church was built as a - as a - as a Sunday school, it - it never matured as a churc
h. It was built in Percy Street on open land, you see, and - it was built - as a partial - as continuation. The school was built with the idea of building a church in the front. So we had to have the school and the church in the same building, and that ap
p
ertains today. Because that church was never built, you see. Now when - and of course - he had a lot of children in those days, 'cos they were bigger families than they are today and - the - the school was more or less - more or less bursting at the seams
.
 Afternoon and - there was always two sessions. One o'clock and two o'clock in the afternoon you see. For the Sunday school. So in - he demanded a certain amount of respect which he had of course. I was only talking to a gentleman the other day and he say
s
, I well remember - being in Sunday school with your father and he always put his finger up and he says, now, until I hear the clock tick you're not going. You see, and - and that was it. But there's one - there's one incident that - recorded. They built 
t
his - school chapel on open land, before Walker Street was built and there were one or two houses in Percy Street, of course that was opened up lately - later. And - the idea was - approached - why not have a boundary wall round the church. And - somebody
 
had the brainy idea, well we'll - we'll have a boundary wall of slabs. And my grandfather said - are we to have the house of God - surrounded by slabs? I propose we have a brick wall and I'll give the first pound. Now a pound in those days was a pound - t
o a man on very low wages. So the boundary wall was built and it's still there you see, on all four sides then. It's still the boundary wall there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Who were considered to be the most important people in the district in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well I suppose
 - socially the vicar to start with, only he was the rector then. Was the rector of Eastwood you see and he used to have a - a curate. A very good living is - Eastwood is. Very good living, used to have a curate and now the mission hall down the bottom of
 
Church Street. Of course he's got a curate now you see hasn't he. Yes, there's a rector and a curate in Eastwood. But - in those days there wasn't much - intercommunion socially or - in the service as there is today with the Church of England and the non 
conformists.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You mentioned the vicar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The rector.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Who else were regarded as community leaders or the important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well of course there was always the - the - ministers of other - other denominations. Congregational church and the 
Methodist men and that kind of thing. But - apart from that not - not - no real - of course there were men worked themselves up from working class to a little bit higher standard, through their own efforts and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What about shopkeepers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, well - of course - the local societies started in 1876. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12994918\charrsid15805719 
The - Langham and Longham Co-op Society. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
That started in 1876. You see, they started in this - this small shop in Canford Road, Langham Hill. And - my father and his - his parents were among some of the f
irst that joined. But - there were - there were private traders in Eastwood you see, name no names but - as had had shops for - generations sort of business and they carried on and they were - they thought themselves a little bit above the - the Co-op - m
embers you see and the man who started it and that kind of thing. Of course -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Who did they associate with, just themselves?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - more or less with themselves, of course quite a few of them had - more - in the church of the local - the Church o
f England you see, they held office. And of course it took - they held office in the local churches you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What about teachers, did they live in the district?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. In the main. In the main.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What sort of social contacts would they have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well I suppose more or less in their own - in their own class you see, there were no - there's no transport in those days, you see - I mean, my grandmother, if she wanted to go to Nottingham she had to go in the carriers cart. It was too far to walk
 to Eastwood or Langley - to catch a train. So she used to go in the carrier's cart to Nottingham, two horses and a van. You see, and so the teachers had to live pretty near, to get - to get to school you see in time and get away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did farmers come into town for social visits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh occasionally they would, they'd come into the market you see and of course they'd have to go to the cattle market wouldn't they I suppose - it'd be Nottingham really. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 In the district the main employers would be the collieries?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
The mines. Yes, but of course - getting near Langley mill there was Lovatt's pottery, there was Smiths flourmill, there was Taylor's engineering works that built collier wagons, you see. And then of course I and Ro Morley at Teesley. I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13513095 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 R Morley and then there was Fletcher's lace, they go back generations with the lace you know. And of course there was - the - the factory at Kimberly, that's - Wolsey. Of course if they want - there's that pottery at Lin croft but if they wanted t
o go further a field they had to catch a train to Nottingham.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You had quite a bit of variety?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes, quite a bit, yes, yes. Flourmill. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 Of course this Aristocs - silk stockings had got - comparatively a - a new. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 It's been going two years of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 But when you were a boy you still had industry other than coal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That were quite important employers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you remember what the employers did on their social occasions, did they mix together at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well the - the Siths, the flourmillers, they were very big - Wesleyans. Oh yes. They were very big Wesleyans. And - the - the Lovatts, they were - well they were more or less Church of England I think. And of course the 
- the - vicar of Heanor - he used to be Canon Corfield and he had - he and interests in the White Start Line. Shipping line. The shipping line, yes, his forbears or his wife, I don't know just how it comes in. Yes. And - one of the - one of them men come 
up to him Guy Fawkes came from Heanor. Guy Fawkes lot, yes, oh yes. That's been brought to our notice recently.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What sort of people would you say went to church as distinct from chapel? Was there any difference?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - no, I don't think so. They 
- they always thought themselves a little bit higher up the social scale if you went to church, I don't know whether there's very much difference in it really. But there was - quite a bit of difference in the non conformists you know. Oh aye, people who w
e
nt to the Congregational church you know they - the same as I say there was - white waistcoats and officials of the colliery and that kind of thing you see. But the Baptist of course, which I - where I was connected, my grandparents and father they were m
ore or less just miners. Miners in the main and their wives and families.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Church played a very important part in the lives of the people in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes. Oh yes. You see - now - most children were sent to school - Sunday school in thos
e days. They were expected to - to go. Twice on a Sunday. That's the reason we had these large - Sunday school communities, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did all the working class have the same standard of living or do you think there were different groups within the work
ing class? You got highly skilled artisans who were regarded as the elite of the working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Then you had the railway navies who were regarded as the lowest level?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were you aware of this sort of structure within the working class when you were a lad?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well - not - not so great I don't think, perhaps just a little bit of difference. And - same as you say, it - a lot depended on - how they spent the money and - some could save and buy a house or get a - pay a bigge
r rent for a more decent house, where others would go to the public and spend it in drink.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 But you weren't conscious of any sharp divisions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No, I don't - I don't think so, not in that sense. Not in that sense, no. I've heard my father say - of
 course had had to have about five or six years apprenticeship and - I've heard him say that his labourer's only getting - a few coppers less an hour than he was getting. So that kind of made a little bit of division in that sense. Yes, that's the old dif
ferential, yes, that's - yes, it's still in industry today. Yes. Yes, that's so, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Can you think of a group within the working class that felt itself superior to the rest? In Heanor the lace workers thought they were a cut above the rest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
 Probably so it did operate there but we hadn't got that in - no, it was more or less mining you see. It wasn't right on the doorstep if you understand. Yes. Yes. Yes, yes, that's so. Yes, that's right. It's similar to what - perhaps not the same analgy b
ut - I can go to one shop and sell a large amount of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15805719  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 goods}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 of one particular kind, you go to another shop and there's no - there's no demand for it. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you remember any families in your district who were thought of as rough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, there wa
s - there was some that - was looked upon as rather rough. Of course it was the way - largely what - how they was brought up. Perhaps the district in which they lived. You see, the - the Brockhills or the Brooky Lees, that used to be looked upon as rather
 a rough quarter at one time. Yes. Yes. it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Any other group that was particularly respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No, I don't - not in that sense I don't think - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was there any big distinction between the skilled craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well ther
e wasn't - there wasn't too many people who served an apprenticeship in the sense of my father but of course there were men who worked in the mine who started as boys and worked themselves up to - butties, deputies, under managers over men, that kind of t
h
ing, where as some of them be content to just carry on - on the old scale you see. In the mine in those days when I was a boy well - when I started to work in the grocer's shop - you see they hadn't the light down the mine as they have today. They had - t
h
ey had blue candles - we used to send them - sell them bundles of blue candles to - to - to take down the mine, and big slabs of chalk that they used to chalk on the coal to see what store it had come out of, and so on you see. Of course it all had to be 
w
eighed as it came up the mine and - there was representative of men who was what they called a check weighman. He checked - he checked the official. Yes, well he was - he'd be a check weighman, he'd be checking the official, you see, so there wouldn't be 
no -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Could you run through the structure of the coal mining industry starting with the actual coal miner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You see, I've never been down a coalmine. No. I lived in the community, yes. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You got the coalminer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was he called anything special or just a miner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Just a miner or a hauler. That's be - he'd - you see, there was no - there's no machines to cut the coal then, it was all done by hand and - he had to have - a certain number of blades and the - the childr
en would have to go to the blacksmith to have them sharpened occasionally so that he would be able to lie on his back and back the dirt from under the coal and then there was what we called a shot firer. That was the man that bored the hole and put the po
wder in and fire the shot, they didn't allow the miners to do that. Special man - special man did that, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 There was the miner and the shot firer, was the next man up the scale the butty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh - he'd be a butty, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And then a deputy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And then a deputy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Who would come above that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well there'd be the under manager. The under manager. Yes. You see, the under manager had to go down in the workings. He went down in the workings, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And the manager was the over all boss.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Yes. Yes. Yes, of course and then the general manager of the lot. Yes, the general manager used to live in - the house where they've built all those houses, bottom, of - bottom of Leather Green - what it - those - I can't think.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You don't mean the bottom of Mansfield Road do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Bottom of Mansfield Road. Coach - well - yes, Coach that's right. And he had a big house off - Coach Drive, that was Coach Road right up to the Barbers house that was, that's a private road, that was Barbers'.
 Well there was one went off that and to a big house on the hill where the general manager lived. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 
He was in charge of the whole - underground and over ground, overground you know of all the - all the workings. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, yes. Yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well more or less I think. They didn't - didn't differ in that sense largely, 'course they had their own individual opinions about certain things and certain people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class? What class would she regard herself as a member of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - well of course with being in domestic service she'd mixed with the people who could employ, not only people in domestic serv
ice but - perhaps had factories of their own and so she saw the other side a little bit but she never - she never looked down on people in that sense.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You were not aware as a child of her thinking of herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You say she'd seen a bit of different sort of social levels hadn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Bit of both sides. Yes, yes, that's so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was it possible at that time to move from one group to another, social mobility or mobility in regard to employment, to better oneself?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh there was an opportunity, you see a man could go from one mine to another. You see, if he thought he could better himself - get a better stall or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I'm thinking of going up without actually having to move.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No, there - it wasn't very blatant I don't think that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You can't think of anybody who started as a coalminer and finished as a manager?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes I can, you see because they'd have to - they'd have to study and perhaps go to Notti
ngham University night school classes. And of course there was the W.E.A. that started then you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So it wasn't easy but it could be done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 It could be done and - not only that, you see - there's the - what is now the Grammar school, we used t
o call it the Heanor Tech - before it was a Grammar school, well the local Co-op society ran - essay competitions and they - they sent - boys from the working class up to the Heanor Tech and paid for their tuition, if they won the scholarship. As a matter
 of fact the man that was - the previous general manager of this - local Co-op society, he was a - I think the first boy that won a scholarship to Heanor Tech. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So the Co-op was actually active in sponsoring education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. They had the education committee as well you see. Oh yes, and they had - 'course they ran all kinds of things you see. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 Eisteddfods}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  and - and groups choirs. Co-operative choirs and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 In those days the education committee of the Co-op wasn't just concerned with adult evening work, it was sponsoring children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh no, they had - they had children as well. Oh yes. Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you remember anyone in the district who was described as a real gentleman or a real lady and if there was why were they regarded
 as such?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well I can't think of anybody off hand at the moment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The term can mean different things to different people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Of course it can. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 
You see - perhaps in the old days he was termed a gentleman as a man as has got a high position and plenty of money and it doesn't always work that way, does it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
I mean, a man can be a gentleman if he goes down the mine. You see. Don't he. Or the other - or the other way about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 There are different interpretations of the same word?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh yes, there was always the policeman on the beat. And - the bobby Walker company had their own - their own policeman. Yes, they employed a man of their own, he was there for good many years.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Security man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
No, he was always on - on - round about the mines and the farms and - you know, round about where it was - their property, on their property. Yes. 'Course he was always in his uniform, more or less. He would be in muf}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 ti}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  sometimes I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What did you think of the policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well - the man that we had was - we really respected him but - on the other hand we - we should have been afraid if we were in the field where we shouldn't have been, you s
ee, playing games and so on but - he would - we should know when he was coming that - what he meant if he said anything and - when he saw the boys running away sometimes he would laugh himself stiff. He was a ruddy - ruddy countenance, very jovial sort of
 chap. Very good, yes. I think that's what we're lacking today, they're not on the beat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How do you think he treated people generally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - fair. Oh yes, fair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your mother ever say, if you're naughty I'll call a policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So you had this sort of threat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, yes, there was like - always used to borrow the - big bad would sort of thing. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 But looking back on it you think he treated people quite fairly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Your home was rented, you were telling me you moved from ....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The Breach - from Princes Street to the Breach.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 When you were in Princes Street, that was a colliery house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And then you moved to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The Breach. The Breach. And th
ey were colliery houses as well but a different type. You see, in the Princes Street they were all in a row. But the Breach was - three - three rows of about eight houses with a - a larger house at each end, and - there was what they called the - the top 
f
ronts and the bottom fronts and in the centre these back garden faced each other you see and there was a - a big corridor down the centre where the - the - horses and carts could come and tip the coal for the miners and where the children could play. Ther
e were no recreation grounds and - in those days as such. No. People had to make their own enjoyment.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 This house was rented so the landlord would be the coal mine owner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That's it. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you ever see him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What the mine - the owner? Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What did you feel about him as a landlord, did you have any feelings about him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh of course - he was kind of remote sort of thing you see, he lived up at Anclose house and was remote and it was the people in between that we - that had contact.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So an agent would actually call and collect the rent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. No, well they used to have their rent stopped out of their wages. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 
And - and then - they had to go to the officers at bottom of Mansfield Road, the offices are still there, there's a clock on the - on the right hand side as you get to the bottom, before you get to Greenhills, there's a very big residence there. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well they used - they used to have to go there for their money. That's where D.H. Lawrence was sent for h
is father's, where I was sent for my grandfather's money. You see. In the big offices. And the - the officials there was kind of portly and - you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What were you sent for the money for, what was the money for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 For the - for the wages.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You went to get the wages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes. It weren't paid at the pit head in those days. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So the miner would go to the office to pick his wages up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That's right. That's so, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And sometimes he might send his son or someone?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Yes, and - and you see if there was a butty he would take the - he would take the packet home, or - it would be taken home and then he'd - he'd - pay out accordingly. You see. According to how much they - they'd got. You see, the men - the men would have 
to come first. And then if there was - more than one butty in a stall you see they'd have to share it. Sometimes there was more than one butty in a stall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Do you remember feeling at any time that your parents had to struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What did you think about that, did you ever think about it as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh yes, because you see I believe it was evident. Mother - mother had to make things go a long way - long way and of course being in domestic service and a cook -
 she could perhaps put her hand to things where other women wouldn't know how, same as you've already said. And we had no expensive toys of course, there were no - no money to buy expensive toys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What difference did it make to the family if your father was ill or out of work, was he ever ill or out of work for a long time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well he - he wasn't - he wasn't ill to that extent, he'd go years without having a doctor you see but - that accident that he had of course he was out a long while.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He would have a sort of provident man anyway would he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He'd made provisions for this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He was a member of the ....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Friendly society.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And it stood him in good stead didn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes. Yes, I can remember befor
e - my - my grandparents had nothing coming in at all, there was no Lloyd George then. I can remember them getting the first five shilling. Ninepence for fourpence they used to call it. You see that's the contribution. Ninepence for fourpence, that's how 
they used to term it. That's how it was termed, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 About 1908 wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes, it'd be about that, yes. Lloyd George we used to call it. Yes, it was called the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 Lloyd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  George.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Apart from that can you remember him being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He was never out of work. No, he was always on job being a trades man he was always in work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your family ever have to get help from the Guardians or the Parish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No. Not to my knowledge. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Where there was someone in the district 
who the people disapproved of very strongly was there any special way in which it was shown? Suppose there was someone who was regarded as letting the side down in a street or a district?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well of course you could always give them the cold shoulder sort of thing. But nothing - no demonstration I don't think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No collective way in which they'd show their disapproval?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. Not to my knowledge, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were you ever given lessons by your parents or a tutor or a governess?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Not - not in that
 sense. We'd - of course we'd - we'd be taught in the home you see, certain things, but we never had a - a teacher apart from - the school. Only a music teacher of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How old were you when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I should think about four. Yes, that was when I went to - the - British schools in Abbot Street, Eastwood. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 When you first started what time in the morning did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Nine o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And come back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Come back - go home for dinner at twelve. Then 'til four you see, one 'til four. Or half past one 'til four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 When you started you went morning and afternoon?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Morning and afternoon, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What kind of school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 A British school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What does that mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well, I - I don't just know
 what the term is - with - - apart from the fact there's a distinction between the British school at Eastwood and the board school where Lawrence went and where I went. That's where - where your boy's going. Bell Lane Board School. Bell Lane Board school.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Your's was called the British school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
It was called the British school. But it was a - it was a school - loaned by the authority because the premises belonged to the Congregational church. Now there was a church school connected with the Eastwoo
d church. See, two separate schools altogether but - where the term British comes in I'm not - not quite sure, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You didn't have to pay to go to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No, not then, my father - my father used to have to do but not - not then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 It was a day school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was it mixed or boys only?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Boys only. There was boys, girls and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 infants}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So the boys were kept separate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How did you get to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Had to walk of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How long did it take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well of course - perhaps be half a mile away, perhaps ten minutes. We had - lingered on the way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 If you wanted to you could walk it in ten or fifteen minutes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Who went with you to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well of co
urse there was - my brother, you see, and there - there were always friends in the neighbourhood, were always plenty of - working class boys you know that - had to go to school. Chiefly working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Where did you have your midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, we had - we went home for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well I so used to like school. Used to like school. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well there's - there's some - there's some good teachers. Of course, the - the hea
dmaster at Eastwood was - named Aldernus. And one of his daughters - went to the same training college at Ilkeston with D.H. Lawrence and the - the rest of the people who - who call themselves the Pagans. He went - he went training at Ilkeston. Ilkeston t
raining centre.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Training for what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
For to become a teacher. Yes. Before he went in - before he went to Nottingham High School. Then he went to Nottingham University. Or University College then, it wasn't a University then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So first of all he went to school at Bell Lane School?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Yes. Yes, because you see - he was born in Eastwood parish and so was I. Well the next house they went to in the Breach - the two rows where we lived was in Eastwood parish and the rows where - the one row where L
awrence lived was in Greesely parish, so he went to Bell Lane Board School. That's right, and that's where I was sent when we moved to Walker Street because we were in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 Greesley}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  parish. Now }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 Greesley}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 parish then before a slice of it was taken over by Eastwood -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719  per}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 acreage was the largest parish in the county of Nottingham. Yes. Well it was the biggest then. But of course Eastwood's taken a good slice over. I think you're in Eastwood parish are you? Oh you're only just on the border. Yes. Yes, well - just whe
re the council house is now, Eastwood council house, where they built the football ground - stood there what they called boundary cottage. There was a name on it, Boundary Cottage, that was the - the end of Eastwood and the commencement of Greeseley. Yes.
 Well I - I used to think a lot of the teachers 'cos the - the only teacher that I remember at Eastwood was D.H. Lawrence. At the British schools. That I remember - I had others as a smaller boy but I - I've - got in me mind more than any.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He was actually a teacher at this school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh yes. Yes, he had two terms at Eastwood British schools. Yes, he had - his first class of which I was a member, I was a pupil in his first class, was in 1902, you see. And then - he went to the Ilkeston training centr
e and won a scholarship to Nottingham High School. Well you see, to pay his fare - to pay his fare by train because he had to walk it from the stations in those days, he came back as a second session to Eastwood school to save a bit of money, to help him 
with his further studies. So - I wasn't in his - the second class that he taught because in the mean time I'd gone to Bell Lane Board School because we'd moved into Greeseley parish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 When he was your teacher at Eastwood British school he would be quite young then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, in his teens, late teens.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Like what they call a student teacher today?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Yes. Yes. Yes, I have a picture in me mind where - he would stand with his piece of chalk poised in his right hand you know, ready to write somethi
ng on the blackboard. And - he had a rather squeaky voice, little bit of a squeak in his voice, rather lanky youth with a lock of hair over his forehead but there was one thing I noticed and always remember and any photograph that I look at and any pictur
e in any books that we see, a certain luster in his eyes. Brilliant luster.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You remember his eyes in particular?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, yes. Yes. 'Cos I shall speak about contact with him a bit later on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So you got on quite well at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You quite liked it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And you got on white well with the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you remember them emphasising certain things in life as being important such as ways of speaking, manners, tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh - oh yes, that was - th
at was generally understood and I think that the teachers used to pull you up if you was - treading over the trades as we used to say you know. Of course - we used to say that they was four - four lessons. Basic lessons at school. Reading, writing, arithm
etic and stick. And stick. When you used to hold your hand out for the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719  cane.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  That's it, yes, that was one lesson.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 If you did something that the teachers disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well if he didn't administer the punishment himself he'd send you to the headmaster.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 But you'd get punished in some way would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How would he punish you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well of course he'd always got the ruler. You see. The headmaster would have the cane. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Girls weren't in your school were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So you wouldn't know whether they got the same punishment as you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 For major offences the head teacher would deal with that would he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 With the cane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did they ask you what you did at school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, they'd ask you sometimes when you came home, what have you been doing at school, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did they visit the school and meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
No, there were no parent - staff associations in those days. Of course if - if the - any child had misbehaved and the treatment administered was rather excessive - you see, perhaps the - the parent would go and see the reason but - it - it wasn't much
 good going home with any fancy stories about what the teacher had done, you see, because you got that little bit of extra you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Can you remember teachers ever singling out children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 
Well - not - not in that particular occasion but - going up to the board school, when I was a boy in the board school - I remember being sent home on a number of occasions because I was 
very good at arithmetic - at algebra and I could give correct answers on the spot, you know, and - the teacher would say, you can go home a few minutes early.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 Well of course there's - there'll always bee a - a kind of a boy that was ahead - ahead above the others sort of thing, self imposed. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 But - there was always little - rivalry between the church school and the British school especially when snow was on the ground. We used to meet on Alexander Stre
et and have a proper - you see, there were not much traffic in those days, so they could do it - without any danger.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Do you ever remember any children who were left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No, I think they was more or less treated on the same level. Of c
ourse - if a boy was - showing a little bit of an extra intelligence I suppose a teacher perhaps - give him a little bit more attention and encourage him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 But you can't remember any children being left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. Not - not - not left out, no, oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You went to different schools, you started off in Albert Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Albert Street.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And then you went to Bull Vale?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I went to Bull Vale.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What age was it when you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I should be - I should think about eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Why did you go there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 We moved out of Eastwood parish into Greesely parish. That's so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You went morning and afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 About the same sort of hours as before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 This was the actual board school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The Bull Vale board school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was that mixed or all boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
No, boys only. There was three sections, boys, girls and infants. I think if you noticed - the stone over the entrance it'll say boys. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you walk to school again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And it took you about the same time did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No, it'd be about the same, a little bit further away but - only about quarter of a mile.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you go with your brother and boys in the district?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes, and the boys in the district.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And you went home for your midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Went home for midday meal.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You still liked school did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Yes, we had some very good teachers there, I always think that was - my basic education at Bull Vale Board School. Some very good teachers there. Especiall}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 y - especially one. Mr Sam Wood w}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
ho was in charge of the seven and ex-seven. That - I meant getting that labour certificate out to show you today. We had - when we left - before we left school at the age of thirteen we had a labour certificate 
to allow us to - to make application for certain jobs and quite a number of - quite a number of boys of my age - went into the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 colliery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  offices. You see, if you was fairly intelligent the headmaster would get them into the colliery offices and some of them stayed all their lives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Start as junior clerk sort of thing would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Start as junior clerks, and one - one became the private secretary to the colliery owner. Oh yes, he got very well up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was the discipline at Bull Vale just about the same as at Albert Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 About - about the same I should think, yes. Yes, you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The same sort of thing you'd get the ruler for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Same sort of thing, the headmaster that I had was different to the one that D.H. Lawrence had because he'd
 retired in the meantime. He was a man with a beard, white beard, Mr Whitehead. But this was a Mr Linley, who was brother to the general manager of the colliery company. They were brothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Your parents }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 still showed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  interest in your school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And would ask you questions about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Would children who went there come from the same type of home as your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Same - same type of home, yes. And perhaps from a wider area because Greesely was a scattered area. You see
, they had further to come. Some of them had to come - boys had to come from Watton, of course they had to stay - stay for their dinner. Bring lunch with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You'd have a sprinkling of farmers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, farmers' children from Watnell and Uull Vale. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That's so. And then on the estate of course - as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You can't remember any singling out of children for different treatment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were gangs or groups any more prevalent or not in this school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
No, I don't think so apart from - when we got into seven or ex-seven - we had a separate little playground. I don't know - you see where the boys}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  section is and the boundary wall, there's a little playground on its own there. And that's where the - wh
ere the - school - teacher, used to get all the seven and ex-seven to play football in the break. We didn't mix with the other - with the other boys. Perhaps it - I don't know whether it was on account of room or - we had a little bit of - of extra attent
ion there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How old were you when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Thirteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Do you think you'd have stayed on longer if you'd had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, I think I should. Yes, but see - in those days - the finance - it were the economics, you see th
e - that played a large part. Especially where there's a large family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you attend any part time education afterwards, such as evening classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. When I - oh yes, when I started work. Yes. Yes, I - I gave up Bull Vale. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So they were run by the local authority then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Yes, I remember earning a prize for an essay competition. Yes, the headmaster took the evening classes, Mr Linley. And of course we had - we had classes at - in connection with the Co-op society and all. Oh yes,
 I've got several certificates. That - I won from there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you ever have any regrets about education in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No, I don't think so, we had the best that - that could be provided for the normal boy in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You think you benefited from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 While you were at school did you have a part time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Yes. Yes I do. Yes. Yes. I think - I was the only one in the family they did a part time job. And - I was a lather boy. In a barbers shop - gents hairdressing - for two years. Yes, for two years I did that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How did you get that job, can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well you see, there'd be - see father going to the barber shop twice a week, well you get to know that they want a lather boy and it just happened - so happened that you wanted to go at that particular time so I - made the application and got the job.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What did you have to do in this job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Put the lather - you see - yes, you see, men - when they came twice or - or once a week naturall
y their beards were growing in that time. And there were a certain technique in lathering. Oh yes, you had to learn the technique. The water had to be very hot, you see, and - and it was - powdered - powdered soap. Powdered soap we had in a kind of a - as
 if you were putting sugar on your - on your pudding you know. See, just - and - and then work it about with your finger and - and put plenty of later on but it was the rubbing in that mattered. By the tips of your fingers. Rubbing in all }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 rounds}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  and of cour
se if you - if the man hadn't a moustache you had to be very careful where you stopped or else he got the lather up his nose - or in his mouth you see. But - there's a certain technique in it and - it was - a penny for a shave and a tuppence for a hair cu
t. And if a man had his own - pot and brush - and be there at a certain time we knew which number pot belonged to which customer, he had to pay an extra ha'penny, he had to pay three ha'pence for his shave if he had his own pot and brush.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 They had their own pot and brush?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The people - the people who could afford it. Or if they were a little bit finicky and thought, well I'd better have me }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 own}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  private brush in case - I get somebody else's - you see, and - it was - there was no haircutting on Saturd
ays. No haircutting on Saturdays, that's the reverse today, because a man - the man had all their time was occupied from eight o'clock in the morning 'til ten at night, shaving as fast as two boys could lather the faces.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What hours did you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well - the - we took it in turn, there were two boys, we took it in turn Monday and Tuesday, and apart from the half day holiday - we - we were there the other two nights together and we were - we were together from eight in the morning 'til ten o'clock a
t night on Saturday, apart from meals.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What hours did you do in the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Seven 'til nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 After school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. And we had - we got half a crown a week for that. Half a crown a week. Now that doesn't sound much. But that half a crown p
aid half the rent, 'cos the house were only five shilling. Rent and rates was only five shilling, it was a decent house. No bath of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You didn't work on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Didn't work on a Sunday, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You didn't get any holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you feel that half a crown a week was a fair wage for what you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well it was rather sweated wage I thought. But - you see, I was - I was there two years and in the meantime there'd been quite a few changes 'cos some of the bo
ys didn't stick it. And - Mr Henson had opened a new - new shop in the area - approached my father to see if he'd let me go apprentice. So I said, no, I'm not having that. That man never sat down to a solid meal on - any Saturday. Always on the go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you give this money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Oh yes, used to give it to help with the family budget. Of course, we might - I might get a bit extra pocket money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You gave her the half crown?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 It depended how things were how much she gave you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes. Yes. That's so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What was the half crown spent on, did it you just go into the general budget?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well it'd go into the general - general family, yes. My father used to have to fetch me home Saturday night. See, 'co
s - ten o'clock at night in those days - it weren't uncommon for men being worse for drink and fighting in the streets in those days. If they'd had a drop too much beer.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How did you get on with the other people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh very well. Ve
ry well. Of course - apart from lathering their faces we used to have to sweep the - the haircuttings up you know and so on. But we got on very well, I got on very well with Mr Henson, he was rather strict. And - after he'd finished shaving a man he'd alw
ays shout - sponge boy. That's when they're there to run round with a sponge and a towel and so on you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He treated you all right did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. And always on the - box on the mantelpiece at Christmas you know, please remember the lather boy. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How did you feel about the work, did you like it or dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well I didn't dislike the work but I didn't like the hours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did the job itself alter your attitude to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you do any other part time jobs before you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
No. There was - there was one thing I - I was a lather boy. You talked to me earlier about cinemas and entertainment. Well at that particular time there came to Eastwood a - a family of amateur actors. Who pitched
 their tent or - erected some kind of place where they could entertain and - they used to give - Sweeney Todd the barber and - Murder in the Red Barn and - that kind of thing you see. And - there was rather an amusing incident but - when once they was hav
ing a performance there would have been a snow scene. Well the word went round that there was no white paper. So immediately the response came, well snow brown then Sow brown. Brown paper. And - being at the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 barber\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  shop you see, they used to send the bills round the locality. And leave a bill in the barber}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
s shop to be displayed and they'd always leave a free ticket. And it was usually the lather boy who got the free ticket so that's one reason I - and then me mother used to say well you've been sitting in
 the swing legs. Where you sat on a plank. And - it was so high you - you couldn't touch the floor. That's it. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What was your first full time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I worked for the - local Co-op Society. There was a mineral water factory, it's now a lau
ndry at Bailey Grove. Still run by the Federation of the local Co-op Societies, but it's amalgamated now. And it was the Associated - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 Beverages}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 , before - but the local Co-op bought it over and that was my first job.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How did you get the job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Wel
l by - application at the - and the word going round - perhaps a notice in the in the shop, certain boys wanted at the Beverage. Used to call it the Beverage then. And make application to the manager and - be set on like that. Of course there was the loca
l committee.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What did you do in this job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well before - before going, we used to have - we had to have a medical examination. And we had to go to Ilkeston, this special doctor under the factories act. Had a medical examination you see. And we sta
rted work at half past six in the morning. 'Til five at night. With a half an hour break for breakfast and an hour for lunch. Yes. Five and a half days a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So when was the half day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Saturday. Always Saturday. Yes, well working in a factory see, Saturday half day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What did you have to do, what did the job consist of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well starting at the bottom of course we - there was always been unloading of the - of the people that have been out delivering the mineral waters. And then - there was
 - the first job, you had to start at the bottom here the same as you did anywhere else you see, was unloading the empty cases with the empty bottles and - putting the bottles in - in a very large square tub filled with water in long trays. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 And when the tr
ay was full you could bring the lid down and clamp it so that - then it was manhandled because there would be about six trays perhaps, manhandled - brought down, then the water started to go into the bottle neck of course instead of floating, this clamp h
eld the bottle down 'till they were full of water, you see, and so on 'til, 'til the whole}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15805719  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 
machine was filled and then they'd have to be left to soak a long time, to soak the - the levels off the bottles and also to - to get some of the impurities and foreign matter out of the bottles. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 'Cos some people have put all kinds of things in bottles. Well then the cleaning of the - of the cases ready for the next thing you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That was a proper cleaning of bottle department?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes, you h
ad to start at the bottom. And - after the - the bottles had been - had had sufficient soaking, perhaps overnight - the tub was heated by steam from the boiler so that you get the water very hot, you see, and the - the bottles were cleaned with a - with b
r
ushes, a boy stand at each end with revolving brushes - worked by pulleys from the machinery you see and we had to put the - the bottle on the bush, until you got all the - the sediment out of the bottle. But we - the most difficult bottles to - to was we
r
e what we called the splits and the minerals. You know those bottles that used to have the - the glass marble in the neck. You see, and then the rubber band in the top. Well - unless you got the - glass marble at the bottom in a kind of a - a ridge in the
 - in the neck - in the neck of the bottle - the - the brush would get fast and sometimes it'd swing round you see and not only spoil the brush but - wet all the boy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 , so it was very tricky. Very tricky job. And when the bottle was washed - of course they w
ere pint bottle you see, that had the brew in and these bottles what we call splits and minerals - was much smaller the mineral, you see. And - then the - the bottles were put on - on a wooden platform, with perhaps nine all different jets. And }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 they were}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  p
ut over the jet and as the platform was turned a jet of water would come with a very high pressure to - to wash the bottle out. And then of course there would be put into the clean cases that had been moved round from one end to the other and carried away
 
to the machines, away to be filled. Or if it was the pint bottles they had to be taken up - to the first floor because that's where the - the brew took place you see. In those days, dandelion and burdock and all those were all brewed, it wasn't essence an
d
 gas. As it is today. It was brewed, properly brewed by herbs you see. And - the manager would put the herbs in a - in a copper container like a - like a huge colander really, when he'd put sufficient herbs in he'd clamp the - the - the lid down you see s
o
 the herbs didn't come out in the process. You see, and they had to be boiled for a certain period and then run into a - a huge vat, about a hundred and sixty gallons, filled with water and then - pure cane sugar added. And then when it got cool - they us
e
d to put - brewery balm on, same as we put balm on our beer to - to work it you see. To give it a bite. Quite a process, but of course the - the mineral waters were - essence and gases. And then - I don't know whether you remember but - those were always 
filled upside down. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 
You see, they're filled upside and the pressure of the - of the gas and of the chlorodine in the mineral water used to force the - this glass bottle into the neck - glass marble into the neck and the rubber band held it tight, 'cos it cr
eated a kind of a vacuum. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 That's why you had to have such a lot of pressure to release it when you wanted to drink the beer. And the siphons - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 siphons}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  of soda water which are sold today you know, press a lever, they were filled upside down as well. And it 
- we had to have three hundred pound of pressure upon the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 gauge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719  before we could fill the si}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 phons. Yes. Now - for that I used to get six shillings a week. Six shillings a week. And in summer time we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 shall}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  have to perhaps stay a little bit longer, to unload 
the - the Foden lorry, we had a Foden lorry, steam lorry in those days. With a trolley, with a trailer on. A Foden steam wagon. With two men, used to go all the distances. And there were two men with horse and the floats that did the shorter distances. No
w
 - while the manager should have picked on me I don't know, but in summer time when an extra brew necessary, you see we ran a brew off in the daytime, and an extra brew'd be necessary so we could do one - commencing the following morning - he would keep m
e behind for an extra hour at night from five 'til six to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 brew.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 This was a boy of fourteen with the responsibility of brewing thi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 s hundred and sixty gallons of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
dandelion and burdock and so on and - having it boil so long and so on, and so on, run it into th
is vat, putting the water and the sugar in, and at the end - he would send his daughter up, this is three storeys high, he would send his daughter up with tuppence. For the extra hour. That was the payment.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you have any holidays with pay there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Not on this, we had no holidays with pay for that then. But in the - in the wintertime you see there were no demand or not such large demand for the mineral waters so we used to pack-egg powder, custard powder, jellies - fruit wines and syrup in jars 
and all that kind - just to keep the staff at work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you feel the six bob a week was a fair wage or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid729553\charrsid15805719 rather}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  - we felt it was rather low for the amount of work we did and the hours we put in. But you see that was all you got in the - in - in a grocers shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you give any of this money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, gave - used to give it all. Then I got so much back as pocket money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Would that six bob go into the general household kitty as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How did you get on with the other people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh very well. Very well generally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And your employer was ....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The local Co-op Society. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Were you treated all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 right by}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Oh yes. There's one thing about - be
fore I left - they installed some new machinery on the lower floor - and so that it did away with the brewing on the top floor and you - it was the same process as the mineral waters, it was all essence and gas, you see. Like a mineral water it was in a p
int bottle, and that pint bottle was sold for a penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you like the work or dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - I - I can't say I disliked it but it wasn't the kind of thing that I would have - had - regular.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You left there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Left there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How long had you been in that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I should think about eighteen months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 And then where did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
I was transferred into the grocery department. Still with the Co-op. It was one - there was one thing that stood out about that. You see - when 
you started in the grocery shop - say at fourteen, you had six shillings a week. And after a year you got a - an increase of two shillings. Now I'd had - about eighteen months at the beverage, being transferred to not the grocer, and these - this was work
i
ng men for you - they wanted me to start again in the grocery shop for six shillings a week. But my father wouldn't have none of that. So after interviews with several committee men I started in the grocery shop at eight shillings a week instead of the si
x. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You started there at eight shillings a week then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I started there at eight shillings a week, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What hours were involved there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well eight o'clock in the morning - 'til - two nights - at six. One at half past five. Of cou
rse we had - always had Wednesday afternoon, close at half past twelve, that was the half day. Friday - but Friday was eight 'til nine. Eight 'til seven on Saturdays. And you see there were no transport. Not enough money to buy a bicycle. So I had to walk
, and that meant taking me lunch every day of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You didn't get holidays with pay in this job either did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well we used to get three days. Used to get three days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You didn't work on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you feel that eight bob a week was a fair wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well it - it was for - for what other people were getting in the - like trades.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 The same happened to that money, it went to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Yes, that's so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You got on all right with the people in this job did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You were treated all right by the Co-op?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Yes. I had to walk about three miles, the first - the first year that I was with them - in the grocery shop. Had to a walk three miles to work. To Harpole as a matter of fact. From Hilltop. That was my first shop. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you like your job or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, I liked - yes, I liked the job. I think I must have liked it stopping in it fifty-two years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You stayed in that didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 I stayed in that. Never knew anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 For fifty-two years and you worked your way up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. I was a manager for thirty-three years. As manager, yes. First small shop and then larger shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 When was it you went into the grocery business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 1908 I started, so it was about 1910. It was 1910 I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You stayed in the grocery business with the Co-op all your working life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, 'course I was in the - I was in the Army three and a half years. First world war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You progressed up to a branch manager?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes, first as - first as - as first hand, that's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11880543\charrsid15805719 the}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  next man to a manager taking charge in the absence. What we called the provision, the man in charge of the provision side, he was the first hand generally and then as branch manager.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Looking back on your working life do you think you might have preferred another type of occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well if there'd have been the opportunity then as there are today, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What sort of a job do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Perhaps in the clerical or - teaching profession or something like that. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You had a period of training really for this job didn't you? You don't just become a grocery manager?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh no. Oh no, you see today there are no grocers in that sense. Everything's been pa
cked. So we had to - we had to have proper training, to pack and wrap and weigh and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did the Co-op have a proper system of training you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Only that the manager in the - in the shop. Yes, of course we could go to classes for - theoretical side.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You went to evening classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, went to evening classes for theoretical side you see. Book keeping. That's right and - grocery and - that kind of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So it would be a kind of apprenticeship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 But it would be a definite training scheme?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you belong at any time to either a trade union or a professional organization
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - well of course we - we were expected to be in our own particular trade union.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Which was USDOR was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 USDOR. Yes. Yes, but - I always objected to paying - a political levy so I - I contracted out. Yes, I contracted out. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you ever take part in any of the USDOR activities?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No, only went to occasional meetings that's all. I was ne
ver on a committee or anything like that. No. See, I was in the church and - Sunday school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
The next question is about employers and workers divisions of interest, of course with the Co-op movement it's a little bit different to normal employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, yes, it is.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you feel generally speaking that your employers and the workers had the same interests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - not always. Because - you see, they were chiefly working men on the committee - and - but they had no power as individuals, the
 only - the only power they had is the fact they're on the board. But some of them carry the same power when they came in the shop. Self - self imposed power if you understand. But - I never thought that - they were quite fair - in some respects in }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 so far}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  
as - we could never get overalls at cost price. No. Always had to pay full - full shop price for overalls. I mean today they have them washed and - laundered and - free and all that kind of thing. See the things are different today to what they were then.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you feel that there were divisions of interest among the workers in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well in those days it was more of a family - family affair. There was more - camaraderie among the employees. Today it's - you see - the motto of the Co-operative movement was, each for all and all for each. But }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 today}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 it's, each for all and all for myself. You see. You see, it's - I mean - speaking to some of the employers now they say there's too much selfishness. It's all me and what I can get.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 In those days you felt there was a greater spirit of comradeship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Oh yes. Yes, we used to have some real - very fine social gatherings. And everyone would - you know - enter into the spirit of it and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Do you think that work changed your attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Well I don't think so, we were always brought up fairly strict and to be honest and straight forward and that's way you've to be in business. You see, because there'd always - there'll always be somebody who tried to pull a fast one. Y
ou see if you look very careful. You see that's happened.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You continued to live at home after you left school didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Continued to live at home, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Do you think that starting full time work changed your relationship with your parents at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No I don't think so. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Or with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
No, just carried on normal. Because you see the two - well there'd be one sister in domestic service then and one brother down the mine and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you spend your Sunday any differently then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. I still - yes - still continued.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 With your church and Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you take any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 None at all. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 What year were you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 1928.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You got married in 1928?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You didn't take any interest in politics did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. I used to vote at - election time. Used the vote election time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you ever vote in a general election before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Before 1919 was - I was - twenty-one when I went in the Army, and I was away three and a half years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So 1919 would be the first general election that you'd vote in then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Perhaps - it was perhaps - what - what month was that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 It was called a khaki election wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Was it? Oh well, I don't - I don't come out of the Army 'til September 1919. I don't remember going to vote then. Don't remember.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you at any time feel under any pressure to vote for a particular party form your employer say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You weren't a member of a political party were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
No, I was never a member, no. Well, I say, not then - but when - since then - we were members of the Liberal party here and Mrs Sharp put up as a councilor. Here there was a Liberal - but it was all
 a hundred percent Labour then of course. If you was - got a Labour tag on you were in. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 So your wife was interested and she was a member of the Liberal party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 At election times then you would work for the Liberals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes, that's so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Any other activities apart from election times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You were telling me earlier about how you spent your spare time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you continue to spend your spare time in the same way or did you do different things now that you were at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well of course - there was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11880543\charrsid15805719 usual}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  activities at the church, Sunday school, choir. Always in the choir you see. And - there's one thing I liked which I might mention - be - I was sent to Hilltop when I was - was - had this - this period at }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 Marpole's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 shop. And so I was nearly near home. I was five years there Very near home and - I - my grandfather's very ill - and in those days they didn't just }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 shrug}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  off the old people and send them into homes, they had more though
t for the old people. So for - two or three years, we had about three years, before going into the forces - right to going into the forces - I slept at me grandmother's six nights a week. Used to leave home after having supper, and go down there you see, 
a
nd spend the night and then go from there straight to the shop. At Hilltop you see, it wasn't very far from Lower Heanor Lane to there. And I did that for - three years, and never complained. Thought it was my - my part of the job - my duty sort of busine
s
s. And of course the - you always enjoyed going to your grandmother's so - it wasn't - it wasn't a hard chore in that respect. And also I did that after grandfather died you see. Yes, right up to going into the Army. They used to allow me Saturday night f
ree to get to go out with me pals.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 You went out in the evening sometimes did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 It was normally on a Saturday with your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes. Yes. Of course we had - went out on Sunday after church as well. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you make any new friends about this time? Boys or girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh of course we always had girl friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 How did you meet them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well meet them at church, just at church generally, or the choir.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you ever take any of your friends home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well only on - special occasions like birthdays or something like that or - these Sunday evening get }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 together}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you have a special friends at that time or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well I'd - oh yes, I'd - one or two special friends among boys and - and girls of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Where did you go with them, normally church activities was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Mainly church activities, yes, or - walks in the evening or something like - we always had socials you know. Sometimes socials on Saturday nights. And - different kinds 
of concerts. I was the - I was the boy who sang the comic songs. At these concerts that we had. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your parents meet your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Well - oh they would do, yes, yes. Especially father 'cos the mother would be at home with the family a good deal you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did your parents expect to know where you were when you went out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh - oh especially if you were late coming home. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Did you have to be home by a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes, round about nine - half past. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Ca
n you tell me a bit about D.H. Lawrence, as you remember him as a boy, a young man, his activities in the district and generally your recollections of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Yes, well, of course the first time I knew him personally was when - he was a teacher, when hi
s first term at the Albert Street school and I was in his class you see. And - as I've mentioned before that's - that's where I knew him and - of course I knew - I knew his father, his mother - his two sisters, but not his two elder brothers. Because - Ge
orge, was the eldest - he died about eighteen months ago at the age of ninety-two. Yes. Well Ernest - was supposed to be the brains of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 family}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 , he went to a job in London, some - some office in London, but unfortunately he died at an early of pneumonia. 
See, so - I knew the sisters. Now - the eldest sister, Emily, married the driver of the Foden wagon. At the beverage }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11880543\charrsid15805719 factory w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 here I worked, the mineral water factory, so I knew him very well. Sam King his name was. He married Emily. Yes, well they had a v
aried career after, as a matter of fact I went and - to visit his daughter only - only the other week, who lives at - at South Moscombe, just the other side of Newark. I knew about her father and - she showed me his - his greatest possession as she though
t - as he - as he used to say. He had a - he had a driving certificate - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 license}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 rather - and it was on parchment and his first driving }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 license}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 was in 1902. So he had this Foden wagon and he was driving different vehicles all the while after you see, so I k
new him very well. And Ada, I knew Ada very well. That was the - the sister that David was very intimate with, those two were real pals in the family, Ada and - and David, you see they used to go out together and go on holidays together. Well she was a sc
h
oolmistress as well. And she married the son of a bespoke tailor in Eastwood, Clark, you see, well afterwards they opened their own business and they got a large draper business in Ripley. Of course there's none of them living now, they're all dead now. G
eorge was the last to go and he was the eldest in the family. And - their - their son is carrying on the business now in Ripley, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Lawrence's father was a miner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He was a miner. At Brinsley Colliery. At Brinsley Colliery. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 
But - really in the - in the books that's written about Lawrence and the impression that he'd give in his - in his novels - of course the names were non-de-plumes but some of them thinks it was his father, some his mother, paving the way and so on. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 But - the - difference in the social status between the mother and the father were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 greatly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719  exaggerated. She wasn't that much superior to him as some people would imagine. No, only - his drinking habits extreme either. Oh they were exaggerated as well, he had his pint of beer I wo
uld think but I - never saw him the worse for drink. But he used to like his pint of beer, but a man who had - a man who would go home and sole and heel his children's boots and shoes and - tell David about flowers and animals and all that kind of thing a
n
d - and so on, he wouldn't spend all his time in the public house would he. No, he wasn't the coarse sort - no, he wasn't. And - and later on I know his brother very well and - and his - two of his nephews, Arthur Lawrence's brother, who was a steward my 
f
ather for the Rising Sun Lodge. You see, and he - and had two sons. As a matter of fact, when we were married 1928, the sons were living down in Bournemouth and one of them had opened a big drapers shop down there. Well the father got us our - our lodging
s
 in Bournemouth for the honeymoon. You see, so we've always contacts there. But as I've told you about D.H., that's as I knew him then, as a youth, and of course as - as we went on to Walker Street we were very near and got to know the family better and -
 on one occasion - in the field opposite the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9598322\charrsid15805719 Lawrence\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
 house which is the third house in the row in Walker Street - on which the Walker Street school is now built, two of us were playing there in that particular field then - I found a pocket knife in the g
rass. Well the other boy, I suppose boy like would say, well I've just lost that, that's mine. Well - I didn't quite believe his story so - we had a tussle for possession. Well just as the struggle was on down come - came the entry which was straight oppo
s
ite you see, this was two houses at one entry, one each side, you called it an entry then, it was kind of a passageway between the two houses, down came the entry a - D.H. Lawrence, or Bert - we always called him Bert Lawrence. He's David Hubert you see, 
w
e called him Bert. He was always known as Bert Lawrence. Yes. Yes. He came down and coming across the Walker Street he said, now what's - what's the matter with you two boys? And so I told him the story, I say's well I've just found this pocket knife and 
-
 this boys says it's his and I don't think it is. Well, he says, to settle the argument I'll tell you what I'll do. You give him the one that he says is his and I'll give you mine. So he - he gave me his pocket knife. Now had I known then that I was talki
n
g to the - the one that was to become the greatest English novelist of this - the first half of this century - I should have hung on to it for dear life. But I - unfortunately I must have lost it. See, so that's - that's a very intimate - acquaintance, th
a
t's the other side of Lawrence. You see, and from then I thought, well - that's one side of Bert that perhaps a lot of people don't know a lot about. Now - when people hear the name of D.H. Lawrence - they say, ah, Lady Chatterley's Lover. Now that's the 
w
rong end to start. They should start at the other end and know the man from the beginning. Because - I used to have a lady come here that was - she wasn't quite a contemporary of his because she was a little bit junior but he taught her mathematics, and s
h
e had a lot of contact with Lawrence and the family. And she used to come here - 'cos I used to write in to the local press about Lawrence you see, impressing on the - the local council it's time they did something in memory of this man who went from East
w
ood who's worldwide known. And they come from all over the world here, Americans and all people to Eastwood to find out where he was born and where he lived and so on. And - in writing in the press and of course she's known 'em a long while, Mrs Millingto
n
 her name was. As a matter of fact she used to go to a - America every two years on the Queen Mary to her daughter's, and she's had invitations to lecture in universities - in the United States, on Lawrence. But she'll never accept the invitations 'cos sh
e
 didn't think she was - in a position to do so. But she came - she came here several times and she - she said, now Mr Sharp, I want to impress this on you. I'll always remember this. That when we young people were together - social occasions or some - any
t
hing like that. If anybody started telling a doubtful story Bert Lawrence was out. He'd have nothing to do with that. Yes, he wouldn't have anything to do with that, and his sister Emily says the same thing. And - her daughter substantiated that when I we
n
t to visit her the other week at East Boscombe. She said, that wasn't the impression that my mother'd give of her brother Bert. He wasn't that kind of boy at all. He loved young folk, girls, flowers and - and bests and so on, you see, and - it's all grown
 up from this - Lady Chatterley business.
