\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Looking back you would regard him as a rather sensitive young man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Oh yes. Yes, rather sensitive. Not only sensitive but sensible. And intelligent. Very intelligent. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11880543\charrsid15805719 Now the people who are setting - who give him great encouragement on his literary carrier was - W.Watkin who was a County Councillor of Nottinghamshire, a great friend of Lawrence, and Jessie Chambers. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 Jessie Chambers we went to visit at the Hags farm. The sister - the sister of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11880543\charrsid15805719 P}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
rofessor Chambers. Professor was the youngest in the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He died last year didn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
Yes. And of course - he was - yes, that's right, well - of course Bert became very friendly with - some of the elder brothers of - of Jessie. But - she encouraged him 
in his - his writings and - I think she would have married him if he had have married her. She fell in love with him definitely. But - you see - Bert - was the youngest son of the family and he was rather little and so he had pneumonia at an early age and
 I suppose his mother kind of - fussed him a little bit. And he got -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7670325 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 He was troubled with T.B. later on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13597539 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10891958\charrsid15805719 
He died of T.B. Yes, but he had this bad attack of pneumonia and - it - it's understood that his mother rather jealous of the attention that
 he was paying to Jessie Chambers. You see, and I think that was the rift that came between them. But - reading his writings, his novels and so on - he brings up quite a lot of things that I'm quite conversant and familiar with. I played the same games ro
u
nd the same lamp post that he did. And that's the same lamplighter going on his rounds twice a night, you know, they used to light the lamp - the gas lamps with a pole. A light in a pole in those days and go and switch them off at night. And also - seeing
 
that the two Hags Farms were next to each other, he used to visit the Chambers and I used to be at the Pearsons, who were my uncle and aunt you see, so I should go up the same path as - go over the same - same fields and in the same woods. That D.H. Lawre
n
ce did, you see, and - as I say, his - his uncle got us our - our - lodgings when we - had our - spent our honeymoon at Bournemouth. Now there's another thing that - that's rather strange when you say the world's a small place. We spent several holidays a
t
